        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "`git log -L<start>,<end>:<file>` is git's **line-range log**. It traces the history of a specific range of lines in a file, walking backwards through commits.\n\nFor `-L<line>,<line>:<file> <commit>` (same start and end = single line):\n\n**What it does:**\n1. Starts at `<commit>` and looks at what's on `<line>` of `<file>` there.\n2. Walks backwards through history. For each parent commit, it computes the diff for `<file>` and asks: *\"did any hunk overlap the line range I'm currently tracking?\"*\n3. If yes ŌåÆ emits that commit, along with the hunk(s) that touched the range.\n4. **Critically, it adjusts the tracked range as it walks.** If a commit added 10 lines above your line, then in the parent commit your line was 10 numbers earlier. Git follows that shift automatically, so on the parent side it's tracking the *correct* old line number.\n5. It also follows the line through renames and large refactors (using a similarity heuristic, like blame).\n\n**Output format** (what `git_log_line_history` parses):\n```\nCOMMIT <sha> <date> <subject>            ŌåÉ from --format\ndiff --git a/file b/file\n--- a/file\n+++ b/file\n@@ -OLD,n +NEW,m @@                      ŌåÉ hunk header\n- old version of the line\n+ new version of the line\n```\n\nThe `+NEW` in the `@@` header is what `current_target_line` gets updated to at `line_history.rs:179-188` ŌĆö that's the line number *as it existed in that commit's new-file side*, which becomes the starting point for walking that commit's authorship-log checkpoints.\n\n**Key behaviors:**\n- It only emits commits where the tracked range *actually changed* (not commits that touched the file elsewhere).\n- It implies `-p` (always shows the patch) ŌĆö that's how you get the `@@` hunks.\n- It cannot be combined with arbitrary pathspecs; the file is baked into the `-L` argument.\n- You can pass multiple `-L` ranges; each is tracked independently.\n\nSo for git-ai's purposes: it's a cheap way to get *the exact set of commits where this specific line was added, modified, or had its predecessor content replaced*, plus the line number that line had inside each of those commits ŌĆö without git-ai having to reimplement diff-tracing across history.",
