          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "## Why `.get(..40)` and `.get(41..)`\n\nThe `--format=%H %aI %s` template produces one line per commit shaped like:\n\n```\ne3b0********41e4 2026-05-04T10:23:11+00:00 fix: cache miss handler\nŌööŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ 40 chars ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆŌöś Ōåæ                          Ōåæ\n                                        Ōöö space at index 40        Ōöö subject (rest)\n```\n\n- `%H` is the **full commit SHA**, which is always exactly **40 hex characters** (SHA-1; SHA-256 repos use 64, but git-ai assumes SHA-1 here, same as `line_history.rs` does at lines 174-176).\n- Then a literal space, then `%aI` (author date, ISO 8601 strict ŌĆö no spaces inside), space, then `%s` (subject).\n\nSo:\n- `output_line.get(..40)` ŌåÆ the SHA. Returns `None` if the line is shorter than 40 chars (defensive bail-out for empty/garbage lines).\n- `output_line.get(41..)` ŌåÆ everything **after** the space at index 40, i.e. `<date> <subject>`. Index 40 is the space itself; index 41 is the first byte of the date.\n\nThen `rest.split_once(' ')` splits that into `(date, subject)` at the next space. The subject can contain spaces freely because `split_once` only splits on the first one.\n\nUsing `.get(..)` instead of slicing (`output_line[..40]`) avoids panics on short/empty lines ŌĆö it returns `Option`, which the `let Some(...) else { continue }` lines handle by just skipping the line.\n\nThis is the same parsing pattern used in `line_history.rs:174-178`, just without the `\"COMMIT \"` prefix (since here we don't need to interleave with hunk lines).\n\n## What `--not <start>^@` does exactly\n\n`git log` takes a set of \"positive\" revisions (include) and \"negative\" revisions (exclude). The output is:\n\n> *all commits reachable from any positive rev, **minus** all commits reachable from any negative rev.*\n\nTwo pieces of syntax matter here:\n\n### `--not`\n\n`--not` **flips the polarity** of every revision argument that follows it on the command line. So in our invocation:\n\n```\ngit log <end> --not <start>^@\n```\n\n- `<end>` is **positive** (include its history).\n- `<start>^@` is **negative** (exclude its history).\n\nYou could equivalently write `git log <end> ^<start>^@` (the `^` prefix on a single rev means \"negate this one\") ŌĆö `--not` is just the multi-rev version.\n\n### `<start>^@`\n\nThe `^@` suffix is a git revision modifier meaning **\"all parents of this commit, as a set\"**.\n\n- If `<start>` is a regular commit with one parent `P`, then `<start>^@` resolves to `P`.\n- If `<start>` is a merge with parents `P1, P2`, then `<start>^@` resolves to `{P1, P2}` ŌĆö both of them.\n- If `<start>` is a **root commit** (no parents), then `<start>^@` resolves to the **empty set**.\n\n### Putting it together\n\n```\ngit log <end> --not <start>^@\n```\n\n= \"commits reachable from `<end>`, except commits reachable from any parent of `<start>`.\"\n\nWhich means: we keep `<start>` itself (it's not a parent of itself), we keep everything between `<start>` and `<end>`, we keep `<end>`, but we drop everything that came **before** `<start>`. That's exactly \"both endpoints inclusive.\"\n\n### Why not just `<start>^..<end>`?\n\nThat's the conventional form and means the same thing in the regular case ŌĆö but `<start>^` literally means \"the (single) parent of `<start>`.\" For a root commit, that parent **does not exist**, and git errors out with `unknown revision`. The `^@` form sidesteps this because \"the set of parents\" of a root is just `{}`, an empty exclusion that git handles fine.\n\n### Merge commits\n\nOne subtlety worth knowing: because `<start>^@` excludes **all** parents of `<start>`, if `<start>` is itself a merge, this excludes both branches' history below the merge ŌĆö which is what you want (everything before `<start>` is gone). Inside the range, merges in `<end>`'s history are still walked normally; `git log` will traverse both sides of any merge unless you pass `--first-parent`.",
