            "new_string": "---\n\n## 14. New `change-history` Command\n\n**File:** `src/commands/change_history.rs` (new)\n\nA new CLI command `git-ai change-history <start> <end>` that returns the full `change_history` (every checkpoint) for every commit in a revision range. It complements `line-history` (per-line view) with a per-range view.\n\n### Invocation\n\n```\ngit-ai change-history <start> <end>\n```\n\nBoth arguments are positional. `<start>` and `<end>` are inclusive on both ends (i.e. the commit object identified by `<start>` *and* the one identified by `<end>` both appear in the output).\n\n### How it works\n\n1. Runs `git log <start>^..<end>` with default output format. `<start>^..<end>` is git's conventional \"both endpoints inclusive\" range syntax ŌĆö it walks every commit reachable from `<end>` minus those reachable from `<start>`'s parent, which leaves `<start>` itself in the set. Newest-first ordering follows from `git log` default.\n2. Parses the default `git log` output directly (no `--format` template). The parser is a small state machine: lines starting with `commit ` open a new commit record, lines starting with `Date:` populate `commit_date`, and the first 4-space-indented non-empty line after the headers becomes `commit_message` (the subject). Body lines beyond the subject are ignored.\n3. For each commit it calls `get_reference_as_authorship_log_v3` and pulls `metadata.change_history`. If the note is missing or has no `change_history`, the commit is still included with an empty `change_history: []` array ŌĆö output stays aligned with git's commit list.\n4. Stripped entries (Default storage mode, where each entry has only `{timestamp, kind, url}` populated) are hydrated via the same `hydrate_stripped_entries` helper used by `line-history`. Cache hits resolve inline from the local CAS cache; misses are batched into a single `read_ca_prompt_store` API call per commit. On any failure (no auth, network error, deserialization error), the placeholder is left in place ŌĆö same degradation behavior as `line-history`.\n5. Emits pretty-printed JSON.\n\n### Range semantics: root commits\n\nThe `<start>^..<end>` form fails when `<start>` is a root commit, because `<start>^` does not resolve. This is the conventional limitation of git's range syntax and is accepted as a known constraint of the basic form. Querying a single-commit range against a root commit can be expressed as `<root> <root>` (which still uses `<root>^..<root>` and therefore also fails); for the root case, callers should query the immediate child instead, or use `git log <root>` directly.\n\n### Output structure\n\n```json\n{\n  \"start\": \"<sha-or-ref>\",\n  \"end\":   \"<sha-or-ref>\",\n  \"commits\": [\n    {\n      \"commit_sha\":     \"<full-sha>\",\n      \"commit_date\":    \"<git-default-date-string>\",\n      \"commit_message\": \"<subject-line>\",\n      \"change_history\": [ <ChangeHistoryEntry>, ... ]\n    },\n    ...\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n`commit_date` is the human-readable date emitted by `git log`'s default formatter (e.g. `\"Mon May 4 10:23:11 2026 -0400\"`), not ISO 8601. This is a deliberate consequence of using the most basic `git log` invocation; downstream consumers that need machine-readable dates should parse this string or fall back to `commit_sha` + a separate `git show -s --format=%aI` lookup.\n\n`change_history` is the **full** `ChangeHistoryEntry` array as stored in the authorship metadata ŌĆö including `timestamp`, `kind`, `conversation_id`, `agent_type`, `prompt_id`, `model`, `prompt_text`, the per-file `files` map (with `added_lines` / `deleted_lines` ranges and `added_line_contents` / `deleted_line_contents` strings), `line_stats`, and the per-entry CAS `url`. There is no per-line filtering ŌĆö this command is the bulk view, where `line-history` is the targeted view.\n\n### Code reuse with `line-history`\n\nTo keep CAS hydration in one place, `hydrate_stripped_entries` in `src/commands/line_history.rs` was bumped from private (`fn`) to crate-visible (`pub(crate) fn`). `change-history` calls it via `use crate::commands::line_history::hydrate_stripped_entries;`. This avoids duplicating the cache-then-batched-API path and keeps both commands aligned on degradation behavior.\n\n### Wiring\n\n- Registered in `src/commands/mod.rs` (`pub mod change_history;`)\n- Dispatched in `src/commands/git_ai_handlers.rs` under the `\"change-history\"` arm\n- Help text added to `print_help()` alongside `line-history`\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Logical Implications",
