          "text": "## `<A>..<B>` vs `<A>^..<B>`\n\nBoth are git \"range\" syntaxes for `git log`. They differ only by what's included on the `<A>` side.\n\n### `<A>..<B>`\n\nMeans: **commits reachable from `<B>`, but not from `<A>`.**\n\n- `<A>` itself is *excluded* (it's reachable from `<A>`).\n- `<B>` itself is *included*.\n- Everything between them (exclusive of A, inclusive of B) is included.\n\nEquivalent to: `git log <B> --not <A>` or `git log <B> ^<A>`.\n\nThis is the form people use most often, e.g.:\n- `git log main..feature` ŌåÆ \"what's on `feature` that isn't on `main` yet\"\n- `git log @{u}..` ŌåÆ \"my unpushed commits\"\n\nThe \"exclude A\" semantics is what you usually want for diff-like workflows: \"show me what's *new* relative to A.\"\n\n### `<A>^..<B>`\n\nMeans: **commits reachable from `<B>`, but not from `<A>'s parent`.**\n\n- `<A>` itself is now *included*, because `<A>` is *not* reachable from `<A>^` (its parent).\n- `<B>` itself is *included*.\n- This is the conventional way to write \"both endpoints inclusive.\"\n\nMechanically, `<A>^` is just \"the (first) parent of `<A>`.\" The `..` operator hasn't changed ŌĆö you've just shifted the left endpoint one commit earlier, so the original `<A>` falls inside the range.\n\n### Side-by-side on a linear history\n\nSuppose history is `... ŌåÆ C1 ŌåÆ C2 ŌåÆ C3 ŌåÆ C4 ŌåÆ C5` (newest right):\n\n| Range          | Output (newest-first) |\n|----------------|-----------------------|\n| `C2..C5`       | `C5, C4, C3`          |\n| `C2^..C5`      | `C5, C4, C3, C2`      |\n| `C1^..C5`      | `C5, C4, C3, C2, C1`  |\n\n### When `<A>^` doesn't resolve\n\n`<A>^` means \"the parent of A.\" A **root commit** has no parent, so:\n\n- `git log <root>..<B>` ŌåÆ works fine, just excludes the root.\n- `git log <root>^..<B>` ŌåÆ **errors**: `fatal: ambiguous argument '<root>^': unknown revision`.\n\nThat's why `--not <start>^@` (which I used in the first draft) was attractive: `^@` is \"the *set* of parents,\" and an em